segments.text: I am Marty Romero, and this is an interview with Mrs. Travis Bryan in her home on the morning of April 15, 1976.
This is part of the Texas A&M Oral History Program.
Because it makes it so permanent.
Oh, I know.
Well, why don't you go ahead and just tell me something about yourself.
I can erase a towel back if I don't want to.
It can be known publicly.
Well, you asked me the question.
OK. Well, you might just start by telling me a little bit about yourself, maybe how old you are and how you got here.
Well, I was born here.
My mother and father were Mr. and Ms. H.L.
Boatwright.
And I was born in 1896, and I've lived here all my life.
And the only time I was gone was when I was away in college.
visits, of course, so I've been right here almost 80 years.
Oh, did you meet your husband here?
It's a wonderful experience to live, I think, your life out in the town where you were born.
At least I have loved it.
I thought, of course, years ago that when I married, maybe I'd move away, but as it turned out, I was so happy that I did get to live here in my place, the place of my birth.
And, uh,
It's just been wonderful.
I have made friends that have been here forever, all my life.
Oh, wow.
That I've known all my life, and I have loved every minute of it.
Well, neat.
Did you have all your children here then?
My mother and father had two other children.
I had a sister and a brother, but I was the youngest one in the family, the baby.
And they were a little bit older than I was.
My sister was 12 years older than I was, and my brother was...
ten years older than I was.
And my mother and father lost a child, a miscarriage, in between my brother and me.
And so that's why there was such a difference between them and me.
But it never did make any difference.
We were all such a happy family.
And I don't know anything in the world about children not wanting to stay in their mother's and father's home.
You know, it's a style now to move out when you've got to be about 16 or 17 years old.
And we had such a happy home.
This is the house my mother and father built when I was six years old.
Oh, really?
This is where I grew up as a child, in this very house.
And we moved up here when I was six years old.
And I got to be seven soon after we moved here.
And school was right across the street.
So the school bell would ring, and I would just wait till it rang.
Then I'd run out the front door and run across the street and be on time for school.
And so it was very convenient.
But then when I got along up in the senior years at school, my father was a Baptist deacon and very active in the Baptist work, the Baptist church here.
And so he and some others went together and built a Brown Baptist Academy.
And it was a Baptist school, a denominational school.
And since my family was such a devout Baptist, he wanted me to leave the public school system
go to the Baptist school.
So I did.
So I did not graduate from the Brown school.
I graduated from the Baptist Academy in high school.
It was the same curriculum and all, you know, same studies and everything, but just different schools.
So, and then I went to Mary Harden Baylor College in Belkin.
I was majoring in music, voice and piano and pipe all of them.
My mother taught me pipe all of them.
Oh.
And so I went to Mary Holland Baylor for two years at Belton, Texas, and then I left to go to New York City.
I didn't graduate from Mary Holland Baylor.
I went on to New York City and studied there, music.
And I had graduated.
I had two diplomas in music, piano.
And then, of course, the man I was supposed to marry, going to marry, was in...
France and Germany in World War I, and so we had to delay our marriage until he came back.
So I didn't get married until 1921, May 17th, 1921.
And we just had one son, he was Travis Brown Jr., and he's at the vice chairman of the board of the First National Vice.
And he has two sons, so I have two grandsons, Travis Brown III and Timothy Norman Brown.
Travis III is a lawyer, and the other one is going to be a banker.
And Travis III is going to come into our new bank.
We're building a new bank building, the First National.
And so the bank, of course, needs a lawyer.
And so he's going to have his office and work in the First National Bank, too.
All my folks have been bankers, right there in the First National Bank.
My father was president of the bank, and my husband was president, and my son was president, and now he's chairman of the board.
My brother was in the bank, vice president.
And we just don't know anything about making a living except in that First National Bank.
And my life mainly has been spent in this home and my church.
I was brought up to be a Christian.
And my mother and father were devout Christians.
They thought that the only way to be excused from going to church was to either be sick or to have a death in the family.
And if someone died and was buried on Saturday, we were in church on Sunday morning.
And so that's the kind of parents I had.
My grandfather was a Baptist minister, F.M.
Law.
And I grew up in a strict home.
I mean by that,
They were not like so many parents today.
My mother and father were here.
When I came home from school, my mother was here.
And they knew where I was at all times.
And when I went out on a date at night, when I was growing up and a young girl, I was supposed to be home by midnight.
And if I wasn't, they just took the town to pieces looking for me.
We didn't play cards.
We didn't drink.
My father said he'd rather have a dozen rattlesnakes turn loose in his house than to have liquor in his home.
We don't know anything about drinking.
I don't have any idea in the world what to even call for if I wanted to drink.
And it's very repulsive to me to see it on television, all these shows.
They don't seem to get in the room, but they all happen to have a drink.
And so they were faithful Baptists.
members of the First Baptist Church and they taught me to be too and so my life has been taken up with my home and the First Baptist Church working for the Lord.

Of course that is the most important thing for anybody but I was going on to say so many young people can't even stay until they're grown but I stayed seven years after I was married in my mother's home.
They were just
so grieved to think that I was getting married.
They were happy for me to marry, but they didn't want me to leave home.
So they had this grand big house.
There's 22 rooms and three stories.
And they began to beg my future husband to let us live in this house.
It's so big, and they were the only ones going to be here because my brother and sister were both young then.
They were older, as I said, than I was.
So there would be just the four of us in this big house.
And my mother just cried.
She said, oh, please don't leave yet a while.
Let me get used to you being married.
My father was the kind of person that said that he would cut off both of his hands before he would strike one of his children.
And so we didn't know anything about spankings or being hit by our parents.
We were just taught right from wrong.
We loved each other so that we did not want to hurt our parents, and so we don't know anything about disobeying and acting ugly and saying other things to our parents.
We just didn't know anything about that.
That wasn't done.
In fact, I cannot recall that there was ever an unkind word spoken between my mother and father and the three children.
We all loved each other, devotedly, and we just didn't know anything about fussing and going on.
My child was born, I was still living in my mother's and father's home, and soon after he was born and was several years old, I decided it was time for us to have our own home.
So my mother said, well, do you want us to give you the walk down there where we used to keep the cows and the horses?
Before we had an automobile, we had a very beautiful Victorian carriage, and we drove two black horses to it.
And they had a leverage driver to drive the carriage and the horses.
And then all of us, as we were growing up, had our own horse to ride horse by.
And we had such a happy home.
And my mother and father loved us, and we loved them.
And it was just a delight to come home.
And this has been such a happy home always.
It still is.
And my husband and I, we hardly had a...
We didn't have an unkind word.
We disagreed sometimes.
He was a member of the Presbyterian Church and I was Baptist.
Sometimes I'd tell him what I believed about my religion and that it didn't quite agree with his.
And I'd say, now you know I'm right and you're wrong.
And he'd say, no, I'm right and you're wrong.
That's about the extent of our disagreements.
I don't know anything about fussing or even arguing with people.
I don't like that.
I don't think Christians are supposed to do that.
We are
to be filled with the love of God and to express that to everyone with whom we come in contact.
And our main work in this life is to win long souls to Christ and to witness to long people.
And if you're going around fussing and acting ugly and blessing people out and using bad words and all such as that, your influence is ruined.
And so we didn't go to cocktail parties and
Well, I never did dance a step in my life.
I don't know one cog from the other.

My daddy said that we had a boy growing up in this house, and that it might be that if we all got to play in cogs and all, that he would turn out to be a gambler, because so many people do gamble with cogs, pussycats, and so now they gamble with most everything.
And so it was strict in that sense, but it was so full of love that you didn't mind the strictness.
You loved it.

And I appreciated my parents because they were doing it because they loved me and because they wanted to keep me out of the penitentiary and make me grow up to be a decent human being and a Christian human being.
And so I praise the Lord every day.
And as I grow older, I appreciate more and more the fact that my mother and father had certain rules.
We honored them.
We knew when mealtimes was and we were here.
We had family worship.
And we learned a verse of scripture, a new verse of scripture every day.
And it's the evening hour right here in this dining room.
This is not the table.
This was a table I bought for my home.
We all had family worship.
Everybody had come to the evening meal.
And we all quoted a new verse of scripture.
And we just loved it.
We loved everybody.
And really, I have never spoken an unkind word to anybody in my life.
Can you believe it?
One time...
Oh, not too many years ago, two women came to my home.
It's when I was living down here.
My mother and father gave us that lot right down there, as I said, where we kept the horses and the cows.
And they said, do you want to build your new home down there?
In the meantime, they had sold the cows, and we had automobiles, of course, and so we didn't need that for the horses and cows anymore.
And so we said, oh, yes, of course we did.
So the little house right down here, right back at me in this same block is the home that my husband and I built, my son and his wife built down there.
And so, what was I going to say?
I forgot my train of thought now.
Anyway, we moved down there in, I think, 1928.
And my sister died in 1927.
She was the first of the family to go.
And then my father died in about seven years.
And then my mother was next in 1944.
And I lost my husband in 1964.
And, of course, my sister-in-law died and my brother-in-law died.
So I don't have any family now except my son and his wife and their two children and the great-grandson.
And of course my grandson is married, one of them is, and he has a wife and this little baby who's three years old.
So that's my family.
And my other grandson works in a bank in Houston.
He's learning to be a banker, and when he has finished the course in that Citizen's Life, the bank in Houston,
He's coming back here to work in Albany, first master plan.
It must be nice to have your family all get back together.
Yes.
This town was named for my husband's grandfather.
And of course, that makes us love it all the more.
He founded Brown.
And Stephen F. Austin, his uncle,
was the founder of Texas, you know, the father of Texas.
And among the 300, he brought the 300, the first settlers of Texas.
The first 300, he was, of course, the leader of them.
So my husband's family founded this town and makes us just love it all the more, of course, and all the more interested in it.
And it's very strange that my grandfather, who was a Baptist preacher,
founded the town that my husband was born in, which was Giddings.
So we had that to life about sometimes.
And there's nothing exciting or interesting about my life.
No one could possibly care anything about it because it's been just very normal and down to earth and nothing great to tell about.
There have been a lot of prominent people in this house.
My brother-in-law was a politician.
And so he had some very important politicians to come here.
William Jennings Brown, who was no kin to my husband.
But anyway, he was a teetotaler, you know.
He always turned his wine glass down when he was invited to social functions.
So when he came here, he was a guest in our home one time, and...
my mother served grape juice, just plain, fermented grape juice, just like we buy out of the bottle now, you know.
So he just loved it.
She told me, she says, don't be afraid to drink that.
It's nothing in the world but just plain grape juice.
So he thanked her, and he told her that from then on, every place he went, when they were all serving liquor and cocktails, he'd say, give me some grape juice.
A woman in Texas taught me to drink grape juice.
But mainly big Baptist preachers were entertained in this home.
It used to be when we had revival meetings here.
In those days, we entertained them in our homes, the visiting preachers, you know.
And my mother and father thought that it was a very wonderful thing, the influence for their home to have these great preachers.
George Turrett, I'm sure you two youngs have heard of him, but he's considered about the greatest Baptist preacher that ever was.
And he was pastor of that big church in Dallas for so long.
And he has been here so many times.
And so, as they say in the White House, Lincoln slept here.
So I can say that George Trude and William Jennings Brown and Joe Bailey, who was a big politician, and just all kinds of important people like that used to come to visit us.
But mainly, my home was taken up with religion.
And most people in the world today don't care about hearing.
Not most of them.
I won't say that.
But so many people are not interested in you.
They don't care about being with you.
You know, a Christian is supposed to be a unique person.
A person who stands out in the crowd.
In fact, a person who does as the Bible says, come ye out from among them and be this separate.
So my life, I'm sure, to most people is very dull.
and dry and uninteresting because so many people are looking for worldly things and people of the world, people who have made a name for themselves in the world.
I'm trying to live so that when I go to heaven, I'll have a nice home to live in.
And I'm sewing on my wedding garment that I'm going to wear to the marriage feast.
And I do honestly believe that the rapture is fast approaching.
Of course, the rapture is when the church is taken out of the world.
Every true believer is going to be called up into the heavens, and that is called the rapture.
First of all, the dead in Christ are going to be called out of their graves.
And those loved ones that you and I took to the cemetery, if they were God's children, they're going to just come right out of that grave.
And they're going to be in the body that they will put down there in.
Only it's going to be revived, of course.
And they're going to look like they did as we knew them.
Only then they will have a resurrected body, like we're getting ready to observe Jesus' resurrected body this coming Sunday.
And then those of us who are on the earth, still living and are saved by the blood of Jesus Christ, we're going to talk life straight up into the clouds and be at home with the Lord.
And then will be the marriage feast.
And I'm working today, and have been all my life since I learned to be a Christian, I'm working on my wedding garment.

Everyone who is a Christian and goes to heaven, of course they will go to heaven, they are saved, will be given a white robe showing that they are saved from their sins and that they are pure and white and clean.
But those of us who work for the Lord will be given another garment called the toga,
And it will be beaded with diamonds and studded with rubies and emeralds and sapphires and all kinds of precious stones.
And the more deeds I do for the Lord and in His name, the more stones, the more precious stones I'll have on my wedding garment.
And I don't crave those things for myself.
I crave them for the Lord because it will show
When he puts that garment on me, it will show that I have been tried to be at least faithful to him and have served him because I love him so.
I don't count what he has done for me and for my family.
He's given me perfect health.
I've never been sick to imagine in my entire life.
In 1954, I was in the grocery store one afternoon, and I had been working in the yard all day, a loft of garden, working the flowers.
And my yellow man had gone, and I ran by the grocery store to pick up some steaks for my husband and me to have that night for dinner.
And one of my friends was standing there, and she said, what's the matter with you?
You're sick.
I said, well, I'm not sick.
She said, well, you certainly are.
I said, well, what makes you think so?
I don't feel bad.
I said, I've been wearing the yellow all day long.
She said, you're sick because your eyes are swollen.
And I said, oh, my goodness, well, I didn't even know it.
So I said to the man in the market, I said, give me my state's right of face.
I've got to go to the doctor.
So I got on my car and flew out to the doctor's office.
It's right as I could to get there before he closed up.
And I said, my friend, Miss Parker, tells me that I'm sick.
He laughed.
He said, she did?
Well, what made her think so?
I said, well, she says my eyes are swollen.
And he looked at me and said, well, they are.
And he took my blood pressure and examined my heart, you know, like they do.
And he said, oh, I don't think anything's serious.
He said, maybe it's just an allergy.
So we piddled around.
I went back to him.
He said, you come back in about a week and let's see how they look in a week.
So I went back.
And instead of getting better, they had gotten worse.
So after several visits with him, he said, you know, I'm not really prepared yet.
He was a baby specialist.
He said,
I'm not really prepared to make all the tests that you need to have made.
So he said, I think I'd better send you to the Ledbetter Clinic in Houston.
So he sat me down there, and it took him four months to find what my trouble was because I was so beastly healthy.
And I had no symptoms of anything being wrong with me except my eyes were swollen, and my skin and my face began to look a little funny.
So finally, after the...
Eliminating all the other possible things that might be wrong with me, Dr. Paul Labella down there in Houston said, well, it's bound to be pure gallbladder.
And of course, he'd been taking all kinds of pictures of it, and it did not show up in a picture, so he decided that that was it, that it was blocked with gallbladder stones.
So my husband and I went down to the Baptist Memorial Hospital in 1955, and on June the 15th that year,
Dr. Aylors, who was considered about the outstanding surgeon in Houston, removed my gallbladder.
It was completely filled with stones.
And so I sat up on the bed, on the side of the bed the next day, and the next day I was walking.
Nothing has ever kept me in bed any length of time.
I've had a slight case of the flu,
I thanked twice, but I didn't go to bed.
I would just lie down more and take a nap in the afternoon.
And then I did have to have this major surgery.

Then I had to go back one time and have my tonsils taken out, and my husband went with me then, and he said to the doctor, he said she never has stopped singing, she never has stopped talking, she never has stopped laughing.
And we got up the next morning and went to Dallas for the weekend, and I ate shrimp cocktails and just had a time of my life.
So my husband said to Dr. Lowe, who was the ER nose and throat specialist in Houston, the one who removed my tonsils, he said, I'm not going to pay you.
You didn't take them out.
So the Lord has blessed me so.
And I had such a good time.
You know, the girls all used to laugh at me.
in my crowd, because I didn't dance, and I didn't drink, and I didn't play cards, and I didn't gamble, and all that kind of thing.
And they said, well, you just might not have any fine dollars.
But you see, the Lord blesses us.
The closer we live to Him, and the more we try to please Him and serve Him, the more He's going to bless us.
So I had plenty of boyfriends.
I used to go with the Aggies.
I went with the A&M professors.
I had a chance to marry a good many of them.
No.
head football coach at A&M wanted to marry me.
He came to New York to see me when I was up there and tried to beg me to marry him up there.
And I had a gloriously happy time.
Not because there was anything about me.
I wasn't any different from any other girl.
In fact, some of them were a lot better looking than I was, more attractive every way than I was.
I was just a plain, ordinary girl.
It was the Lord.
showing me that you did not have to be a worldly person to have a good time.
And the closer I have found all my life, the closer I live to him, the more the blessings flow to him.
The other day I noticed that my feet were swollen.
And I thought, oh, no, I certainly don't have an inch of strength to go to the hospital and go through the clinic.
I just thought it would kill me.
And so I thought, well, I have a Heavenly Father who knows exactly what's the matter with me.
I'll ask him.
So I said, Oh, dear Heavenly Father, please tell me.
I'm going to close my eyes and I'm going to ask you, Lord, to open the Bible when you want me to see the answer and tell me if I'm sick, if I need to go to the hospital.
Of course, I will if I have to.
So this is the way I pray when I want a fast answer.
So I closed my eyes and I picked up my Bible and I said, Now, Father, please open it to the verse you want me to see.
So I opened it, and this is the verse.
My eyes fell right on that verse.
Thy faith hath made thee whole, go in peace.
And I said, oh, thank you, Lord.
Praise your holy name.
I don't have to go to the hospital.
And in just a very few minutes' time, he said to me, you're eating too much fermented cheese.
You know, I don't like to cook anymore.
My husband's not here, and I'm by myself, and I have arthritis.
I don't feel like cooking anymore.
So I'd been eating too many pomada cheese sandwiches.
He let my feet swell to call my attention to the fact that I was doing something wrong.
So he told me what it was.
So I quit eating pomada cheese, and the swelling was gone the next day.
Then when I went to Houston to have that gallbladder operation, my husband's face was as long as from here to college.
He just knew I was going to die because I never had been sick.
And so he put me in that Memorial Hospital down there.
And that night, before surgery, he had gone on over to the hotel to go to bed in his room to be back for my surgery.
So I said, now, Father, talk to the Lord.
I said, I know you know whether I'm going to live or die.
And I said, I'm ready to go to heaven any time you want me to.
I don't mind dying tomorrow morning.
And I'm ready to die.
But I said, I certainly would like to know.
My husband is so sad.
He's just worried to death.
Is there anything you could tell me that would cheer him up a little bit?
And I said, now I'm going to take the Bible and let you open it with my hands and tell me what's going to happen to me during this operation.
So this is the truth that I ever told him.
He opened the Lord, opened my Bible.
My eyes fell on this verse.
The sickness is not unto death, but for the glory of God.
That the name of the Son of God might be glorified.
So I'm the happiest person here.
I wanted to get out on the floor and kiss it because the Lord was in there and I was just shouting all night.
And a little while, the nurse took a hand in the door and she said, it's time for me to give you a pill to make you go to sleep.
I said, no.
She said, I see you're nervous.
You're scared because you won't go to sleep.
I said, no, I'm not scared at all.
I said, please don't come in the room.
I said, God is in here and I'm visiting with him.
And I'm not going to take a pill.
And I'm not scared.
And I'm not going to die.
And I know I'm not going to die because God has told me to.
And so I said, if you will, please don't come in right now.
I don't want to interrupt my visit with the Lord.
Then one time I...
I had to go to the dentist.
I had an infected tooth.
And the doctor said, well, you just have to put it.
That's all.
So he pulled my tooth, and it was way back in the back of my mouth.
He said, Ms. Brown, I'm awfully worried about this.
He says, it's badly infected, and I'm so afraid the poison is going to go to your brain.
I said, oh, Dr. Ritchie, I don't think it will.
I said, I'm healthy.
Nothing ever happens to me.
It was Saturday, and so I said, I've got to hurry on home and
Studied my science school last year.
So I came out.
He said, well, you come back in a week.
I said, all right.
So I came out home and just almost forgot about it.
But when the next Saturday came, I remembered I had an appointment with him.
So I went back and he said, well, you see, he x-rayed it.
He said, the poison has gone to your head.
And he said, oh, Ms. Brown, he said, it's dangerous.
He said, you've got to go to the doctor right now.
He had an open throat now immediately.
I said, well, doctor.
